Red Wine Data Exploration by Christian Guzman

This report explores a data set containing quality rating and other attributes for approximately 1,600 red wines.

The first plot is a histogram showing the distribution of the quality.

Since there are few wines rated below 5, and above 7 the data will barely be noticeable. As such I will combine the quality ratings.

##    Poor    Good Premium 
##     744     638     217

Wines rated from 3 to 5, 6, and 7 to 8 will be labeled as Poor, Good, and Premium respectively.

## [1] "integer"
##  Factor w/ 3 levels "Poor","Good",..: 1 1 1 2 1 1 1 3 3 1 ...

The new feature rating is a factor of 3 levels. We can use this new feature to analyze the data in new ways.

The bar graph shows each level with a significant amount of wines. Premium happens to have significantly fewer data that Poor and Good wines.

I would describe the majority of the plots to be skewed. Specifically, all variables except for pH and density have obvious right skew. With residual.sugar, chlorides free and total sulf dioxide as having strong right skew, and long right tails.

Fixed acidity (Tartaric acid): We can see that most wines have fixed acidity value between 6 and 9 g/L.

qplot(x = free.sulfur.dioxide / total.sulfur.dioxide, data = wine)
with(wine,{
     summary(free.sulfur.dioxide / total.sulfur.dioxide)}
     )

I wanted to get a look at free sulfur dioxide divided by total sulfur dioxide because I felt this proportion value would give more information. I know from online research that wine makers strive for a certain percentage of free sulfur dioxide to combat bacterial growth.

From the above summary, the min percentage was approximately 2% with the median being 37.5% and the max was 86%. It would be interesting to discover what is the prefered percentage of free total sulfur dioxide for the higher rated wines.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset contains 12 features, with 1,599 observations. One extra feature X is simply an index and was removed from dataset. The sulphates feature is also excluded from this analysis. rating feature was created from making quality into a 3 level factor.

##  [1] "fixed.acidity"        "volatile.acidity"     "citric.acid"         
##  [4] "residual.sugar"       "chlorides"            "free.sulfur.dioxide" 
##  [7] "total.sulfur.dioxide" "density"              "pH"                  
## [10] "alcohol"              "quality"              "rating"
length(wine[!complete.cases(wine)])
## [1] 0

There was no missing data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest is the created feature rating. The attempt is to explore what features factor into the decision of the experts to rate a wine high or low.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The main features of interest for me are those that have obvious affect on the taste of the wine such as the acidity features (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid), residual sugar, density and alcohol, PH, free and total sulfur dioxide.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created the variable rating.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I applied log transformations for the heavily right skewed data such as: fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, and residual sugar. I did this to lower the influence of outliers in order to better view the data. I also made quality into a nominal variable of 3 levels. This is important because I have to take into account that my dependent variable is categorical.

The strongest correlation found was between fixed acidity and PH. This is an obvious one because pH is a scale used to acidity. In this case the more tartaric acid in the wine the lower pH it has. I expect to see similar results for the other acids (volatile acidty, citric acid).

## [1] -0.5419041

While citric acid and pH has a pearson score of -0.54. Citric acid contributes to over 50% of the variance in pH and like fixed acidity, the more of this acid the lower the pH suggesting higher acidity.

Applying the jitter and alpha transperancy I can see three clusters where the data points are heavily concentrated in. There is also a vertical band on the left indicating wines with 0 citric acid have varying pH values.

## [1] -0.5524957

It is interesting to note that if fixed acidity tends to increase citric acid and if volatile acidity decreases citric acid this could be the same as saying that fixed acidity improves the freshness of the wine, while too much volatile acidity tends to decrease it.

The visualization does appear to show a vague downward slope as volatile acidity increases.

More citric acid seems to be an important aspect to premium wines with a clear trend for higher ratings having more of it.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

The main feature of interest, quality was most strongly correlated with alcohol and volatile acidity.

There was no clear visible trend for fixed acidity and rating nor was there for residual sugar and rating.

Better wines tend to have higher proportion of free sulfur dioxide.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

As fixed acidity content increases citric acid and density also tend to increase. But as fixed acidity increases pH value tends to decrease, indicating an increase in acidity.

Citric acid is strongly correlated with fixed acidity and volatile acidity. The pearson scores are 0.67 and -0.55 respectively.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Fixed acidity was negatively and strongly correlated with pH, positively correlated with citric acid and density.

free sulfur dioxide was also strongly and positively correlated with total sulfur dioxide but this is to be expected since free SO2 is a portion of total SO2.

From this exploration and analysis I might not want to use fixed acidity with pH, citric acid, or density to reduce colinearity between the explanatory variables to better understand the relationships between the independent variable and the dependent variables.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Yes, Using scatter plots comparing features with quality rating as the color factor I was able to view clusters of wine groups. The best visualizations for this where: Fixed acidity vs.citric acid, fixed acidity vs.density, volatile acidity vs.citric acid, and citric acid vs.pH. I knew from this that I should try to use most of these features in any model.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Yes I was surprised that citric acid and volatile acidity modeled wine quality groups pretty well. Citric acid was more important than I thought it would be before starting the analysis.

Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I created a multinomial logit model. It is good for cases when the outcome variable is categorical with more than 2 levels.

The model was able to generate coeficients that supported my explorations of the the data. Volatile acidity had a negative coefficient, and alcohol a positive one, for example. From this I was able to interpret how the model would use the features in computing log odds for predictions.

The model however had a large Residual Deviance value of 2537.765, for a multinomial logit the deviance is preferred to be smaller. This could be that the features were not the best choice or there are still features that are not in the data that assist in creating a model.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

From this visualization it was observed that most of the wines were rated 5 or 6. Very few other ratings were given relatively. Due to this the decision was made to label wines with rating 3 to 5 as Poor, 6 as Good, and 7 to 8 as Premium wines.

Plot Two

Description Two

Higher rated wines tend to have higher alcohol content and less acetic acid. I expected this trend because it was stated in data set text file that volatile acidity can contribute to a strong vinegar taste in the wine. While higher alcohol seems to be an important characteristic to wines.

Plot Three

Description Three

Premium wines cluster at higher citric acid content and lower acetic acid content.

Reflection

The wine data set contains observations on nearly 1600 red wines, and initially contained 13 features with no missing data. I explored the structure of the data and identified the most important features and those that would not be important to the analysis. I saw that the Quality were ratings made by wine tasting experts. The minimum and maximum values were 3 and 8 respectively. I combined the the ratings into appropriate bins to make up for small amount of data for certain ratings like, 3, 4 and 8. By combining the ratings into Poor, Good, and Premium groups I was able to make data readings more legible.

The outcome variable Quality was most strongly correlated with Alcohol and Volatile Acidity features with pearson scores0.5 and -0.6 respectively. Of all the pairs of correlations the strongest pearson scores were between Fixed Acidity vs.pH, Citric Acid, and Density.

A limitation of this dataset is there are so few ratings except for 5 and 6, making me have to bin the data. I had to make the decision of which ratings would be poor and which would be best without the domain knowledge. I also think this data could benefit from a machine learning algorithm and feature selection to create a stronger model. Despite that with the multinomial logit model I identified features of significance (alcohol, volatile acidity, citric acid, and freeSo2).
